{
  "local_port": 36406,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I have completed my b.tech in Dec 2016 and want to start preparation for UPSC from Delhi can anyone guide me plz?",
  "response": "Certainly! Starting your UPSC preparation in Delhi can be very advantageous due to the availability of coaching institutes, libraries, study material, and a competitive environment. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you prepare effectively:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Understand the UPSC Exam Pattern**\nThe UPSC Civil Services Exam (CSE) consists of three stages:\n1. **Preliminary Exam (Prelims)**:\n   - General Studies Paper I (200 marks)\n   - General Studies Paper II (CSAT, qualifying with 66+ marks)\n2. **Main Exam (Mains)**:\n   - 9 papers (Essay, GS I-IV, Optional I-II, English, and Indian Language)\n3. **Personality Test (Interview)**:\n   - 275 marks\n\nFamiliarize yourself with the syllabus and exam pattern for each stage.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Plan Your Preparation**\n- **Duration**: UPSC preparation usually takes 1\u20132 years of dedicated effort.\n- **Start with Prelims**: Focus on clearing Prelims first, as it is the qualifying stage for Mains.\n- **Optional Subject**: Choose an optional subject based on your interest, background, and scoring potential.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Create a Study Plan**\n- **Daily Schedule**: Allocate 8\u201310 hours daily for preparation.\n- **Weekly Goals**: Set weekly targets to cover specific topics.\n- **Revision**: Regularly revise what you\u2019ve studied.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Recommended Study Material**\nHere\u2019s a list of essential books and resources:\n\n#### **Prelims**\n- **General Studies**:\n  - NCERTs (Class 6\u201312) for History, Geography, Polity, Economy, and Environment\n  - *Indian Polity* by M. Laxmikanth\n  * *History* by Bipin Chandra, NCERTs\n  * *Geography* by G.C. Leong, NCERTs\n  * *Economy* by Ramesh Singh\n  * *Environment* by Shankar IAS\n  * *Science & Technology* from newspapers and magazines\n- **Current Affairs**:\n  * *The Hindu* newspaper\n  * *Yojana* and *Kurukshetra* magazines\n  * Monthly current affairs compilations from coaching institutes\n\n#### **CSAT**:\n- *CSAT Paper II* by Tata McGraw Hill or Arihant\n- Practice previous years\u2019 question papers\n\n#### **Mains**:\n- **Essay**: Practice writing essays on diverse topics.\n- **GS I-IV**: Refer to standard books and coaching notes.\n- **Optional**: Choose subject-specific books.\n\n#### **Interview**:\n- Read newspapers and stay updated on current affairs.\n- Practice mock interviews.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Join a Coaching Institute (Optional)**\nDelhi is home to many reputed coaching institutes:\n- **Vajiram & Ravi** (Rajinder Nagar)\n- **Chanakya IAS Academy** (Delhi)\n- **Drishti IAS** (Mukherjee Nagar)\n- **Vision IAS** (Karol Bagh)\n\nCoaching can provide structure, guidance, and peer interaction, but self-study is equally effective if you\u2019re disciplined.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Join Test Series**\n- **Prelims Test Series**: Join test series from Vajiram, Vision IAS, or Insights IAS.\n- **Mains Test Series**: Practice answer writing regularly.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Use Online Resources**\n- **YouTube Channels**: StudyIQ, Unacademy, Vision IAS\n- **Apps**: PIB, PRS India, ClearIAS\n- **Websites**: Mrunal.org, InsightsIAS, IASbaba\n\n---\n\n### **8. Stay Consistent and Motivated**\n- Read success stories of past toppers for inspiration.\n- Stay focused and avoid distractions.\n- Join study groups or forums for peer learning.\n\n---\n\n### **9. Stay Updated on Current Affairs**\n- Daily Newspaper Reading: *The Hindu* or *Indian Express*\n- Monthly Magazines: *Yojana*, *Kurukshetra*, *Pratiyogita Darpan*\n- Government Sources: PIB, PRS, Government reports\n\n---\n\n### **10. Practice Answer Writing**\n- Start practicing answer writing for Mains early on.\n- Focus on clarity, structure, and time management.\n\n---\n\n### **11. Mock Interviews**\nOnce you clear Mains, prepare for the interview by joining mock interview programs offered by coaching institutes or online platforms.\n\n---\n\n### **12. Stay Healthy**\n- Maintain a balanced diet.\n- Exercise regularly to stay fit and focused.\n- Take breaks to avoid burnout.\n\n---\n\n### **13. Utilize Libraries and Study Centers in Delhi**\n- **Central Library** (Delhi University)\n- **Delhi Public Library**\n- **British Council Library**\n- Study hubs like Karol Bagh, Mukherjee Nagar, and Rajinder Nagar\n\n---\n\n### **14. Important Websites**\n- UPSC Official Website: [https://upsc.gov.in](https://upsc.gov.in)\n- PIB: [https://pib.gov.in](https://pib.gov.in)\n- PRS: [https://prsindia.org](https://prsindia.org)\n\n---\n\n### **15. Stay Positive**\nUPSC preparation is a marathon, not a sprint. Stay patient, work hard, and believe in yourself.\n\n---\n\nIf you need further guidance or have specific questions, feel free to ask! Best of luck with your UPSC journey! \ud83c\udf1f",
  "temperature": 1.0,
